  "facts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Clayton’s roots trace back to just before the Revolutionary War, making it one of New Jersey’s oldest boroughs.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.claytonnj.com/1203/Borough-History"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Today Clayton boasts a close‑knit community of about 8,000 residents who celebrate its heritage and growth.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.claytonnj.com/1203/Borough-History"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The Clayton Historic Preservation Committee curates displays in the Borough Hall, schools, and post office, keeping history alive for locals.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://guides.gcls.org/member-community-info/clayton"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Residents rely on the nearby Glassboro branch of the Gloucester County Library System for books and community events.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://guides.gcls.org/member-community-info/clayton"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Jacob Fisler’s 1800s purchase of 2,800 acres around Cedar Green Cemetery laid the groundwork for Clayton’s early development.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        29
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.claytonnj.com/1203/Borough-History"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "In 1875, a wave of “boroughitis” led to Clayton’s formal incorporation, reflecting a broader trend of small towns seeking independent governance.",
